quran[9]{c,v,t,f}:
  16,94,"And do not use your oaths as a means of deception among you, lest a foot slip after being firm and you taste misery for barring<i class=""s"">(others) </i>from the way of Allah, and for you there will be a great punishment."
  16,95,"And do<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>not purchase, in exchange for Allah’s covenant, a small price; indeed, what is with Allah is better for you, if you only knew."
  16,96,"What you have runs out, but what is with Allah remains. And <span class=""h"">We<sup foot_note=""80407"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span><span class=""h"">will most surely repay</span>those who were patient their reward in accordance with the best of what they used to do."
  16,97,"Whoever has acted righteously, whether male or female, while being a believer—We will most surely grant him a good life, and We will most surely repay them{1}their reward in accordance with the best of what they used to do.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  16,98,"So when you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>recite the Recital{1}seek refuge with Allah from Satan, the outcast.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is Qur’an which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  16,99,"Indeed, he has no authority over those who have attained faith and in their Lord they place their trust."
  16,100,"Indeed, his authority is only over those who take him as an ally and those who through him associate<i class=""s"">(others with God) </i>."
  16,101,"Yet whenever We substitute a sign in place of another sign—and Allah{1}knows better what He <span class=""h"">bestows from on high<sup foot_note=""80411"" class=""qiraat"">2</sup> </span>—they say, “Indeed, you are nothing but a fabricator.” Rather, most of them do not know.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from 1st person to 3rd person.
  16,102,"Say, The Holy Spirit has bestowed it from on high from your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord{1}, with the truth, in order to strengthen those who have attained faith, and as guidance and glad tidings for Muslims{2}.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from 3rd person to 2nd person.The Arabic word used is Muslimeenwhich means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
